  "prompt": "You're telling me money laundering isn't illegal?",
  "response": "No, money laundering is **absolutely illegal** in most countries around the world. It involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear as though it came from lawful sources. Money laundering is a serious crime because it enables criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and fraud to thrive.\n\nGovernments and international organizations actively combat money laundering through laws, regulations, and enforcement agencies. For example:\n\n- In the **United States**, the **Bank Secrecy Act** and the **Patriot Act** include provisions to combat money laundering.\n- Globally, organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** set international standards for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts.\n\nIf someone suggests that money laundering isn\u2019t illegal, they are either misinformed or attempting to mislead. It\u2019s important to recognize that engaging in or facilitating money laundering can result in severe legal consequences, including hefty fines and imprisonment.",
